	<div id="main">
                
		<h1>Simple WCF Client by contract and without svcutil</h1>
<div class="entry">	
	<p>Sometimes your <abbr title='Windows Communication Foundation'>WCF</abbr> based Sever and Client, both have access to the contract assembly (common approach in .NET Remoting, btw). There is good chance to reduce your code. Well, at least client code. Look at the following code:</p>

<pre><code>public MyCoolService Create()
{
	var factory = new ChannelFactory&lt;MyCoolService&gt;(new WSHttpBinding());
	var address = new EndpointAddress(&quot;http://localhost/ MyCoolService.svc&quot;);
	return factory.CreateChannel(address);
}</code></pre>

<p>As per name <a href='http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms576132.aspx'><code>ChannelFactory</code></a> is a factory. And it will create fully functional client. And yes, it works :).</p>

<p>In our application, we use <abbr title='Windows Communication Foundation'>WCF</abbr> web-services for communication between components. This stuff made <abbr title='Web Service Definition Language'>WSDL</abbr> and auto-generated proxies redundant. And we dropped many code. I think this is good thing.</p>

<p>Enjoy!</p>
	<p class="entry-info">This entry was posted on 2009-10-22T12:01:00+00:00. <a href="http://chaliy.name/blog/2009/10/wcf_client_without_svcutil">Permalink</a></p>
